title: For Sale/Trade:  Springfield P9 competition gun package deal
postcontent: Price Drop: I've got a WICKED bad Springfield P9 in 9x21 I'd be willing to sell or trade.  VERY accurate gun, it has a WCPI (World Class Pistols Inc.) 6 inch barrel, long slide with no porting, compensator (with 3 ports), short single action trigger, skeleton hammer, ambi safety, extended mag release, scope mount with carbon fiber side panel, Tasco PRO point red dot scope, wood checkered grips (very slim and comfortable), and this one has the rounded style trigger guard as opposed to the more squared off version sometimes seen on the custom P9's.  Pistol comes with 4 weighted factory type 17 round mags and I'll toss in someone's "bubbafied" high capacity mag that still needs some TLC to sort it out (fits, but jams about half through a full load).  For the re loader/competitive shooter I've got (if the math is right) 1,915 brass 9x21 casings... 1,637 of those are brand new unprimed brass Starfire, 84 once fired brass casings, 197 new primed casings.  I also have 4 or 5 boxes of Winchester and Fiocchi 9x21 factory loaded rounds, and I probably have a bag of 50-100 or more of my own once fired factory brass that I managed to pick up at the range out back.  I'm just thinning the pistol herd a bit, not hard up to sell this baby.  Cash value on this one I'll say $1,250 or I would work some trades for rifle or rifle/pistol combo.  All laws must be followed, CCW or pistol purchase permit required.  This would either be an excellent gun for competitive shooting or a great piece for someone's collection.  WCPI pistols are fairly rare and were built by the well respected George Huening.  Many of his parts are still used by competitors today, he was very cutting edge at the time and his guns, scope mounts, etc. were in many magazines back when he was first building (he's back into shooting I see with his son).  Also this gun will fire 9x19 rounds, but acted up on me last time I tried it with a Jericho/Mossad type mag... it ran fine with 9x19 in the Springfield P9 mags the other times I've fired 9mm, so I think it was just that mag.  I generally run 9x21 though the gun but have tested on occasion with 9mm on several occasions... only had feeding issues with the one mag and only had the one spare Jericho mag on me that day to test with.

postcontent:
The Milt Sparks holster is an IWB Nexus leather holster made for 4" 1911 models with the use of a 1.5" belt.  Used only once or twice.  No need to wait months for one.  Price is $100.

The paragraph below is from the Milt Sparks website. 

"The Nexus has several new features as well as some old tried and true. The most unique feature being our new self closing, neodymium magnetic loop (Patent Pending) that has the same holding attributes as the traditional one-way snap, but is much easier to align and fasten to the belt. The steel cup portion of the closure shields the belt from putting direct pressure on the loop closure that might cause accidental separation as sometimes happens with regular snaps. And because you don’t need to allow for additional room in the loop like you would need to work the one-way snap, a smaller, closer fitting loop can be had with less slop."

The Wilson Combat is an OWB Lo-Profile shark skin holster for 1911 models 4" to 4.25" with a 1.5" belt.  Typically out of stock on Wilson's site.  Used very little.  Very comfortable and looks great.  Price is $140.  

Both holsters look like new and have been used very little.  Only selling because I just sold my Kimber Pro Carry, so I have no use for them.  If someone is interested in both, I'd take $220 for them.
